    "recap_headline": "Troy University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "TROY, Ala.\n- Troy exploded for 13 runs in the first two innings, and it was all it needed to defeat Old Dominion 13-4 to even the series on Saturday.\nThe Trojans (7-11, 1-1 SBC) batted around in each of the first two innings, chasing ODU (9-8, 1-1 SBC) starter Darin Kuskie after just one frame. Troy pounded out five hits in the opening inning, including one from each of its first four batters, and scored six runs.\nNolan Book\ncapped the rally with a two-run single.\nThe power came in the second innings when the Trojans scored seven runs, blasting three homers. Catcher\nJimmy Janicki\nlaunched a two-run homer 407 feet, his seventh of the season and fourth in the last three games. Right fielder\nZaid Diaz\nwent back-to-back with Janicki, as the Chipola College transfer went opposite field for his first Division-I homer over the left field wall. Book capped off the fun with a three-run homer, his first as a Trojan after transferring from Mount St. Mary's, giving him five RBIs on the day.\nOn the mound, left-hander\nBenjamin Stubbs\ngave the Trojans seven quality innings. The senior pounded the strike zone, allowing zero walks to four strikeouts, allowing four runs - three earned - on nine hits. It's the third consecutive start that the Flagler transfer went at least six innings, though Saturday's win was Stubbs' first as a Trojan.\nFreshman\nMatt Dill\nshut the door in the final two innings, retiring six of the seven hitters he faced. The righty struck out a season-best three hitters while allowing just one hit.\nNotables\nTroy's pitching staff walked zero hitters for the first time this season.\nBenjamin Stubbs'\nseven innings were tied for the longest start of his career. He's done so twice this season and four times overall.\nFreshman\nMatt Dill's\nthree strikeouts were a season high.\nTroy hit three home runs in the second inning. It's the first time they've homered three times in an inning since April 14, 2024, at App State.\nTroy's offense drew seven walks and five HBPs, which is the most free passes they've drawn in a game this season.\nSteven Meier\nreached base four times out of the leadoff spot, going 2-for-4 with a walk and and HBP.\nJosh Pyne\nimproved his hit streak to five games with a 2-for-5 day at the plate.\nAaron Piasecki\nwent 2-for-4 with a walk and two RBIs. His six multi-RBI games this season lead the team.\nPiasecki played second base for the first time this season. He played 55 games at second base for Central Michigan last season, and has started games at shortstop, centerfield, and right field for Troy this season.\nJimmy Janicki\nhomered for the third consecutive game. He's the first Trojan to do so since\nBrooks Bryan\nhomered in four straight games from April 20-27, 2024.\nJanicki went 2-for-5 with three RBIs. His ten multi-hit games this season lead the team, and his five multi-RBI games rank second.\nZaid Diaz\nhit his first Division-I home run in the second inning.\nDrew Nelson\ndrew a career-high three walks.\nTy McGraw\nmade his first career start. He went 0-for-2 with two HBPs, including one with the bases loaded in the first inning for an RBI.\nSean Darnell\nstarted at first base for the first time this season. Previously, he had only played first base in the bottom of the 12th inning of Troy's win at Georgia, as starting first baseman\nBlake Cavill\nhad been pinch-run for in the top of the frame.\nNolan Book\nwent 3-for-5 with a double, a home run, and five RBIs. His three hits were a season high, and his five RBIs tied his career high.\nQuotables\nHead Coach\nSkylar Meade\n\"When you have innings when you score a lot, multiple pitchers are used, it can be difficult. I thought Stubbs handled it like an ultimate pro. And the part that tells me he handled it like a pro isn't the seven innings, only three earned. It's the fact that you don't walk anybody. It means you're commanding your body. Commanding your mind. You're understanding the assignment, and you're in attack. If you're in attack, the game always rewards you.\"\nNolan Book\n\"Steve [Meier] started us off. Gave us the momentum. We strung hits together and played well, swung the bat well.\"\nBenjamin Stubbs\n\"You pitch to the lead is what I've always been taught. You keep getting outs, you keep getting going. If they get one, that's fine, because you've still got six more runs you can give up. You've just got to keep pitching and keep doing what makes you successful.\"\nNext Up\nGame three between Troy and Old Dominion is slated for 1 p.m. on Sunday at Riddle-Pace Field."
